  "prompt": "Can you go on both Kickstarter and Indiegogo at the same time? What are some of the companies who have done it, concurrently or sequentially?",
  "response": "Yes, it is possible to run a crowdfunding campaign on both Kickstarter and Indiegogo, either concurrently or sequentially. However, there are some important considerations to keep in mind:\n\n1. **Platform Policies**: Kickstarter and Indiegogo have different terms of service. Kickstarter typically requires exclusivity during the active campaign period, meaning you cannot run the same project on another platform at the same time. Indiegogo, on the other hand, is more flexible and does not enforce exclusivity.\n\n2. **Audience Overlap**: Running campaigns on both platforms simultaneously may dilute your audience or cause confusion. It\u2019s usually better to focus on one platform at a time to maximize engagement and momentum.\n\n3. **Sequential Campaigns**: Many creators run a campaign on one platform first (e.g., Kickstarter) and then follow up with a second campaign on Indiegogo (often using Indiegogo\u2019s InDemand feature, which allows ongoing fundraising after the initial campaign ends).\n\n### Examples of Companies That Have Used Both Platforms:\nWhile specific examples of companies running concurrent campaigns on both platforms are rare due to Kickstarter\u2019s exclusivity policy, many have used both platforms sequentially. Here are a few examples:\n\n1. **Pebble Time** (Smartwatch):  \n   - Pebble first launched on Kickstarter in 2012, raising over $10 million.  \n   - Later, they used Indiegogo\u2019s InDemand feature to continue raising funds after their Kickstarter campaign ended.\n\n2. **Flow Hive** (Beehive Innovation):  \n   - Flow Hive started on Indiegogo, where it raised significant funds.  \n   - Later, they appeared on Kickstarter for a follow-up campaign.  \n\n3. **Exploding Kittens** (Card Game):  \n   - The famous card game launched on Kickstarter and became one of the most funded projects in the platform\u2019s history.  \n   - After the campaign, they used Indiegogo InDemand for continued sales and engagement.\n\n4. **Oculus Rift** (Virtual Reality Headset):  \n   - Oculus initially ran a Kickstarter campaign, raising $2.4 million.  \n   - After the campaign, they utilized Indiegogo\u2019s InDemand to continue engaging with backers.\n\n### Key Takeaways:\n- Running campaigns on both platforms **concurrently** is generally not advisable due to Kickstarter\u2019s exclusivity policy.\n- Running campaigns **sequentially** (e.g., Kickstarter first, then Indiegogo InDemand) is a common and effective strategy.\n- Always review the terms of service for each platform and plan your campaign approach accordingly.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
